European inflation slid into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying growth in the price of food products.
The price increase in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent, the Luxembourg-based Union Statistics Office announced.
Official forecasts only gave a probability of 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut core interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "negotiate" on inflation so that later it does not have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the twelve-year record; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation soared in the euro area as a result of rampant food and energy prices.
Wheat forward quotations increased by 88 percent and soy quotations reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more was paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 a barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will already decline to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent over the next 3 or 4 months, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to cut interest rates twice during 2008.
