The most expensive is the Auchan, the Tesco has quintupled its prices
They maintained the average price level rise of 16 percent in the hypermarkets of the Buda<0xC3><0xB6>rs gold trading triangle, with the difference that this year the VAT has not been increased.
Article by Napi Gazdas<0xC3><0xA1>g
This year also saw an average increase of 16 percent in the commercial gold triangle of Buda<0xC3><0xB6>rs the usual Christmas basket of the daily Napi, but in all hypermarkets there was a growth well above the thousand HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already “fired” in December of last year, so there was no drastic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they can not do it for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10,573 HUF.
(In 2003 this basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, walnut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in the Auchan we have also found one kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was also surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with a two-liter redistributable bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in the basket of Napi Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, with respect to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15 percent, while Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18 percent the prices listed in Napi’s basket.
Comparing last year’s most expensive basket values with this year’s cheapest basket values, the difference has been 12 percent, while growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during last year’s Christmas prices felt the rise in VAT.
It was precisely this process that destroyed trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the margin of prices to be applied to each product and to calculate the effect of price change on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of a product’s circulation, he may lose a significant profit in the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, which the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF to the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
This year there were no such extremes, since the highest price today has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased by 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two Christmas seasons, there was a catastrophic growth in prices in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of consumer goods grew by more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some staple foods, recorded a price increase of more than 30 percent over the 12-month period.
So for example, in addition to the wheat, also in the case of the egg.)
According to the basket of Napi, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, there was, in the worst case, only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, being able to impose the drastic increase in prices even to multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our experiences, most consumers of the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking for pallets the canned food.
On Wednesday morning, the three stores formed large queues in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that inside the country the sales volumes are lower, numerous multinationals complain to the survey institutes because the income is below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
Many Hospitals Save on Disinfectants
This year several thousand infections caused primarily by the improper application of antibiotics have been registered in hospitals.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overloading of staff do not favor infection control – says the doctor-head of department of the National Center of Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is even saved with disinfectants.
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of contagion occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
An injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after the MRSA infection and since then no major surgical intervention has been possible due to the presence of the bacterium in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 cases of hospital infection caused by multidrug-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multidrug-resistant agents has been safely recorded, the rest of the information is not available.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One-third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g., throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once antibiotics are over-applied or improperly applied, the bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics are transformed into bacteria that are highly resistant to antibiotics and quickly spread under inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicemia in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with the weakened organism, to the elderly or to people of low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital there is nothing special in MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, the nursing staff treats them in rubber gloves and mask and there are appropriate antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalised patients are pre-examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and infection with multidrug-resistant pathogens - says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Because this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should screen hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their bodies.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to light when MRSA infections are already visible in the patient,” said the epidemiologic center’s chief medical officer.
The European Union makes strict recommendations for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be done to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples are even less frequent in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
Save on Disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is spread from one patient to another through health personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, however, also in this sense considerable shortcomings are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is contagious through droplet transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately you can also experience - added Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz - that in hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater probability for infection.
In the opinion of Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, where the appropriate preventive measures are complied with, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multidrug-resistant agents (among them MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
