Fodor and the Six Percent Hungarians
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor, the expert-level meetings will end on Tuesday and on Wednesday after the official opening will continue the negotiations at the ministerial level on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Roadmap, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
There are currently lively discussions on the particularity between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that at the moment it does not want to negotiate precise figures, although it tends to agree that compared to the situation in 1990, by 2020 the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect will decrease by 25 to 40 percent.
Another major theme of the conference is whether industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing or unwilling to offer material and technological assistance to countries in need.
A further agreement was reached on the aid to be offered to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member board of directors, probably within the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes the "Piac és Profit".
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment and Hydrology Minister G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to preserve its leading role in global climate protection and promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The minister said that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 percent by 2020, compared to 1990 levels, regardless of whether or not the “post-2012 agreement” will be signed and is willing to commit to reducing even 30 percent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to comply with their commitments.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor noted that the countries signatory to the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to decrease by 5.2 percent, within which the then 15 EU member states committed to meet an 8 percent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6 percent the emission of gases responsible for the greenhouse effect with respect to the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will meet - notes the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
There is a lot at stake in Bali, since within two years we will have to sign the international agreement on long-term climate policy, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international system of emission reduction, which was recently endorsed by the International Committee on Climate Change (IPCC).
With this, the reduction of emissions would suffer a delay and an increase of more than 2°C of the Earth's average temperature could not be prevented, a fact that according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor release footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operations corps, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from the soldiers of the air force that have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had uploaded the videos for recruitment purposes, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true purpose of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda costs practically nothing compared to conventional recruitment TV spots, defence expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC, but they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans made a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the recklessly edited and censored recordings, amateur videos also appear in the distributor, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of losses, without however presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have been uploaded to the Internet and numerous videos recorded in real operations, but the British army is only lately taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruitment with free downloadable shooter video games, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
