Banks want to solve the crisis
The US Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian Central Banks decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be received in the money market through tenders.
In these tenders, banks auction the interest rates at which they are able to lend money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will send out to bid for $40 billion, and then another $24 billion will be facilitated by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This step should solve the biggest economic problem, i.e. the continued growth of the shortage of free capital that banks could lend,” Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report for clients.
“This coordinated action by the central banks likely reduced the U.S. recession from 65 percent to 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already spent $60 billion on unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
“Central banks must really be afraid of what awaits them when they decide to take this step,” said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
"It seems that the situation is really bad," he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems of access to loans and that they will therefore have to lend more expensively to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with different impacts on global economic growth.
The central banks thus decided, after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for money lending in the interbank market.
This means that the banks were constantly afraid to lend money even when the US Central Banks, Canada and Britain lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"It will have the same effect as another interest rate drop," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some economists are not surprised that the step taken by central banks helps to ignite the crisis because it does not solve the fundamental problem that is the fall of the real estate market in the United States.
