The Serbs and Albanians of Kosovo have concluded a sixth and final session of discussions in Baden, Austria, on Wednesday morning, without having been able to overcome their differences over the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status," European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger told a news conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was " at stake", his American counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their efforts to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of negotiations.
"We do not foresee violence for now but we are entering a very difficult period," he added, noting that "obvious tensions exist."
End of mediation on December 10
The mediators of the troika, which regroups the European Union, the United States and Russia, will go to Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The future of the 90% Albanian-populated province could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko return their relationship to the UN Security Council, by December 10.
The talks in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final session of negotiations since the troika was tasked with a new mediation by the UN last August.
Americans and Europeans believe that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the granting of independence in Kosovo in the Security Council, insist on pursuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
“Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution,” Botsane-Khartchenko said.
Declaration of Unilateral Independence?
After eight years of UN administration in Kosovo, Westerners consider independence under the supervision of the European Union to be the only viable solution.
Pristina feels ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not resolve in its favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," said Fatmir Sejdiu, president of Kosovo's autonomous authority, at the Baden hotel where these "last chance negotiations" had been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future prime minister of the province, has given part of his condolences.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that has led to homicides and deportations."
" Domino Effect "
Serbian President Boris Tadic, for his part, has considered that a compromise was always feasible, warning the Albanian majority of Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of independence of the province.
Belgrade particularly fears a " domino effect " in a region still weakened by the wars of independence in the 1990s.
"For Serbia, he said, this does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision belongs exclusively to the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has a veto.
" The Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word "
"Only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica had said.
