Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which entered into force on 1 November
In parallel to its parliamentary process, which ended today with the vote by Congress on the amendments incorporated into the bill in the Senate, the government has submitted to a public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the aim of both entering into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the effort made by deputies and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulations in order to ensure the protection of investors and regulate in detail the activity of the entities so that the markets function efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves the modernization of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and encouraging cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new regulation will allow financial advisory services to be provided to both specialized firms and individuals or legal entities and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory societies (AFI), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of operations on financial instruments, so that the regulated secondary markets are joined by multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment services companies to disclose on the market information on the key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and forms of risk management and requires them to keep a record of all the operations they carry out, in order to facilitate the supervision by the CNMV.
In its passage by the Congressional Economic Commission, several modifications were incorporated, among which it highlights that securitized debt is considered a "complex" financial instrument given its high risk to the investor, which has been demonstrated with what happened with U.S. high-risk mortgage debt (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delimit the functions that graduates can perform in Economics and Business 30 years after the adoption in 1977 of the royal decree that delimits the professional functions reserved for economists.
For its part, the Senate incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as the mediator, who will work on behalf of others, will not require the authorization of the CNMV and will be able to provide its services of marketing products and attracting clients to different investment companies at the same time.
