Which insurance is right for me?
Car insurance, which covers the driver in the event of possible accidents, represents an important expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, sex, age of the car, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use of it, among others.
Having a car is just the beginning.
And that is, choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the vehicle model.
First of all, we need to be clear about what we are talking about.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insured.
This commitment is embodied in an insurance contract, which states that the company receives the value of the agreed premium in exchange for being responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is established taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, age of the card, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use that is given to it, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so the more likely they are to suffer an accident, the higher the fee to pay.
It is for this reason that both older than 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, as statistics reflect that they have a lower casualty rate due to their prudence.
Also, by looking at the numbers, the companies have come to the conclusion that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use that is given to the vehicle will influence the frequency, and thus the likelihood of having some sort of perchance.
As the frequency increases, the odds increase.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
That is why the driver has to study the situation well to choose the car insurance that best fits his profile.
We will show here the most significant variables when choosing one or another type of insurance, so that this, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insured, offers you a reasonable price.
Young people under the age of 25 face various disadvantages when it comes to taking out insurance at an affordable price, such as reduced driving experience and the age of the ticket.
Although the ideal thing to be well insured is all-risk insurance, there are other more economical options.
The most cautious drivers can opt for an all-risk franchise, so they get insurance coverage at all-risk but at a more feasible price.
This kind of agreement would mean that the customer pays a part of the amount of the claim.
"The part of the amount of the claim provided by the customer will be pre-set based on the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount," said Luis Noguera, chief executive in Spain of First Europe, online insurance mediator.
Another option is extended third-party insurance, so that the customer ensures protection against damage caused to third parties, although not against those caused in his own car.
In addition, it would be covered by theft, fire and loss of the vehicle.
A piece of advice.
If you are under 25 try to be careful and avoid damages as much as possible, as this will affect the bonus, and may reduce the cost of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction on the base rate the company owns.
On the contrary, a penalty is a surcharge on such a base rate.
“Bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and its profit.
If the company has had a good year it will be able to afford to increase bonuses,” Noguera explains.
After the age of 25, drivers find it easier to take out insurance, since the accident rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
For this reason, the most recommended thing is to hire a full risk with a franchise.
“Normally young people cannot make use of the experience previously gained in the time of an accident, and even in the time of driving,” says the director in Spain of the European company, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, once the ‘fear of the novice’ has passed.
However, if the client is married but does not yet have children it is preferable that he negotiates insurance at all risk, as long as his financial situation allows, of course.
For their part, marriages with children are considered by insurers as the public with the lowest casualty rate, so the surcharges will be lower.
In this case, the best insurance would be one at all risk with a deductible (it can be 300 euros), or, when there is a high level of bonus, one extended to third parties from the third year of life of the vehicle.
“They conduct more relaxed driving and have greater purchasing power to afford the luxury of taking on a greater amount of franchise,” Luis Noguera said.
For retirees, it is advisable to take out an all-risk insurance with a deductible (this being 150 euros), or one extended to third parties when you have a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is something important, not only because it covers the driver in the event of possible damages, but also because it represents an important expense, which is why it is essential to properly study the insurance that suits us best according to our personal situation.
