Mitt Romney says it’s not worthy for presidential candidates to answer the questions of a snow ape.
However, Republican presidential candidates eventually agree to hold a debate on YouTube, in which ordinary voters record questions on video and send them for dissemination among the candidates.
None of the questions posed on Wednesday afternoon were more ridiculous than that of the snow ape who asked Democrats about climate warming in the YouTube Republican Party debate.
But the questions, and the answers, this time reflected much of the state of the Republican party in the run-up to next year’s election.
It is not known exactly how the CNN producers, who co-sponsored the debate, chose YouTube videos to show candidates to applicants.
But the first half hour of debate, the longest devoted to a single topic, focused on immigration.
The topic is one of the most powerful topics for Republicans.
CNN asked a group of undecided voters to raise the dial when they heard ideas they liked: the broadcasters noticed peaks of approval when candidates spoke with extremist arguments.
The hardest word exchanges of the night were between Rudy Giuliani, the national pioneer, and Mr. Romney, who has been a trailblazer in the crucial Iowa and New Hampshire polls.
Mr. Giuliani is trying to ruin Romney’s reputation because he was soft on illegal immigration when he was mayor of New York.
He attacked Mr. Romney, accusing the former Massachusetts governor of hiring illegal immigrants to work in his home.
Both responded aggressively when asked if a candidate could support an “amnesty” (allowing illegals to regularize their situation and giving them the chance to obtain citizenship).
Minor candidates such as Duncan Hunter, a California congressman, and Tom Tancredo, a Colorado congressman, reached agreement on the issue.
No one has the word of being a nominee, but both remain in the race perhaps because both warned about the issue of immigration before the others.
At least in immigration, and in general terms, candidates share views: increased border surveillance, intolerance of illegal immigrants.
This topic, along with fear of China’s toxic toys and other concerns abroad, helps Republicans forget about, or minimize, the divisions between liberals and Christian conservatives.
But the debate turned into uncomfortable when other topics appeared.
Mr. Giuliani was asked why he had supported gun control in the past.
John McCain and Mr. Romney debated whether water immersion should be considered torture.
One person asked if the candidates believed every word of the Bible.
This led Mr. Giuliani to stumble into the position that while the Bible was his favorite book, he did not literally believe in the story of Jonah and the whale.
Another person asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee – now against all odds, first in Iowa’s most recent poll, thanks to his long-standing Christian conservatism – said the death penalty was painful but necessary.
When pressured to answer whether Jesus would be in favor, he laughed saying that Jesus was too smart to be a candidate in the elections.
The race is still unusually open.
Mr. Huckabee is on the rise in Iowa, coinciding with liberal Ron Paul’s fundraising campaigns, and his heated statements from Wednesday’s debate.
The two have come out from the bottom, because the two wings of the party did not come to an agreement on the most famous and traditional candidate.
In 1980 and 2000, a candidate joined the party early and convincingly with a winning message about the greatness of America, satisfying both wings of the party.
This time the match is split and the result is far from clear.
Dolores Laboristas
Gordon Brown has discovered another hole in which to sink; but it also emerges
As political scandals continue in England, this one is not particularly interesting.
They don’t seem to have sold influences, nor are they exorbitant hotel accounts in Paris, nor are they sucked by extramarital fingers.
But it has been revealed that a wealthy businessman has disguised contributions to the English Labour government party, worth more than <0xC2><0xA3>650,000 ($1.3 million), for nearly four years using false names, and that the party did not denounce him.
Two months ago, when the prime minister evaded calling an election, foolishly insulting British intelligence by declaring that opinion polls did not influence his decision, the hope was that it would provide a strong and efficient government.
But instead, like Vince Calbe, the liberal Democrat leads with increasing ingenuity, because the dreaded Mr. Brown has gone from being Stalin to being Mr. Bean.
The bailout of Northern Rock, a troubled bank, demonstrated regulatory weakness and poverty of judgment in times of crisis.
Poor proposals to change the tax code have pitted business groups, together, against the government.
The tax authority lost 25 million personal data that revealed an unimaginable administrative lapse.
A trio of retired generals began a riot in the House of Lords, protesting against cuts in military spending: being ministers of the armed forces is, they claimed, a part-time job.
Now it is the multiple donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour secretary general (and former accomplice) has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown walks irrevocably towards the exit.
Governments can reach a turning point after they find themselves unable to govern.
People don’t believe them as politicians, but they usually suspend their disbelief when a new batch takes over.
Once it is clear that the prime minister cannot improve things, that he does not have much time left, that suspension is too much: public officials begin to fail; cabinet ministers are exposed; the press is looking for bad news; and the government gets defensive and does not focus.
On the one hand, Brown’s position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders he cannot defend himself by arguing that it is new.
Although I would like to disown Tony Blair, he was his lieutenant-colonel.
The Northern Rock problems and the authority registration tax are related to the decisions Brown made as chancellor of the treasury.
And even though it’s not directly involved in Blairish setbacks — or “effective for partners,” research funding political parties — voters can assume it is.
However, Mr Brown's situation is not as bad as it seems.
The plates are not as bad as the Tories want to show.
As in Mr. Bean, no one has died or been directly scammed.
And the remedy, though painful, is to give what Mr. Brown’s naturally Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable and brutal government.
The new political scandal of donations is a good example.
Mr. Abrahams, who compares his donations to charitable gifts, says he does not want public recognition for his benevolence.
This may be the case, but the decision is not his.
The anti-anonymity laws for big political taxpayers are clear and there is a clear reason: the public has a right to know who is buying access to those in power.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew about Mr. Abraham's deal, and that it was not illegal, will obviously face Jon Mendlesohn, the fundraiser chief who was asked about the donations in October.
But Mr. Brown is so far uninvolved: there is nothing to suggest that he knew of these performances, although the bulk of the payments were made after he took control of the office in June.
So far, the prime minister has done half the work.
He has been quick to condemn his party for breaking the law, but is diluting himself in decision-making over a family matter, a commission of inquiry into the matter—led, to a large extent, by a judge and a bishop.
In this case, the morals are not complicated.
If the law has been violated, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things that Mr. Brown must do, such as finding a permanent and independent head for the Public Life Standards Commission, since he has not had one for six months, and he must also push for a genuine reform of party funding.
This will require arduous cooperative work by the Labour with the Tories, and perhaps a renunciation of the special financial situation with the unions – bitter measures for a partisan like Mr. Brown.
But he must face some partisan facts.
The Conservatives now have a good level of support in the polls; he has two years to win voters; and the only way he can move to victory is to act with impeccable probity and solid competition.
Sharks cards
The subprime mortgage crisis is infecting the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is natural for dorsal fins to swim excitedly around.
Today, as the U.S. housing market is in crisis, predators have their sights set on the country’s credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses could reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis infects other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of infection are already visible.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been amortized or that are more than 30 days late respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken 1.4 million charge in its U.S. consumer finance business, in part due to the weakness of card borrowers.
However, it is too early for panic.
Delay and crime are at low levels.
According to Moody’s, a rating agency, in the third quarter the crime rate of 3.89% was almost a percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the U.S. Bankruptcy Act (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a large credit card loss; the number of applications (and therefore of lateness) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were worsening.
The industry also reports solid payment rates, which show how much of its debt consumers pay each month.
And the reliance on credit cards and asset-backed securities is fairly firm, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts that emissions for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of crisis infection between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge debts to credit cards now that credit institutions are phasing out.
But credit card issuers look more at the flow of liquidity than asset values, so falling prices don’t necessarily drive a change in borrowers’ creditworthiness.
They can even work to outsmart the emitters.
Incentives for consumers to keep amortizing the mortgage decreases if the properties are worth less than the loan value; and as a result, payment of the card debt goes up the priority list.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to the difficult conditions that mortgage lenders face, changing interest rates or altering creditor balances.
That should, in theory, reduce the risk of a rapid asset freeze.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and reassess all the loans,” says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer of Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If house prices are lower and a credit crunch pushes America into recession, the industry is undoubtedly facing a more severe future.
We need to keep an eye on those dorsal fins.
British bankers found guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers who went on trial for their responsibility in the frauds with Enron’s former chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow, were found guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew were originally found innocent of seven counts of fraud for colluding with Fastow in a secret financial operation in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of employees.
They were sent to trial in January.
But during the hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each was convicted of collusion in fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich Natwest, a unit of the Scottish group PLC at the Royal Bank, became notorious in Britain for extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, his case marks the sluggish end of an investigation launched after the Enron collapse in 2001.
Initially, the charges against the bankers were to have alerted Fastow in 2002 that he was the target of a government investigation into Enron's downfall.
The indictment against the bankers - dubbed the "NatWest Three" - alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to invent a fraudulent scheme with Fastow and his former senior aide, Michael Kopper.
Greenwich Natwest had invested in a subsidiary of an Enron corporation controlled by Fastow, who was the mastermind of a myriad of Enron frauds, which helped his spiral into bankruptcy.
In 2002, the bank valued the subsidiary's interest at zero, but the three Britons knew it would rise.
A company under Kopper’s control bought the subsidiary’s bank interest at $1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for interest in the company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely represented Enron, as the energy company would pay Greenwich NatWest $20 million for its parts of the subsidiary.
But the 20 million remained in the hands of the British bankers, Fastow and others.
The bankers collected $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others received about $12.3 million, according to the indictment.
In January 2004, Fastow was convicted on two counts of conspiracy in the Enron collapse.
The trio of Britons were arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence in a Louisiana federal prison.
Kopper is serving a three-year and one-month sentence in Texarkana.
Each of the three British bankers must pay the $1 million they required to live in the United States while the trial was being held.
Enron, one of the nation’s seven largest companies, declared bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks, could not hide the debt of millions or make their failing businesses look successful.
The collapse led to the loss of thousands of jobs, more than 60 million in market values and more than two million in pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and previous chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were indicted last year for their roles in the company's collapse.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay’s conviction for conspiracy, fraud and other charges was suspended when she died of a heart attack last year.
