But this is a small expense for some of the rich Russians.
“It has a capacity of up to 18 passengers,” says Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
“But no one asks for that model of so many seats because it’s for family private flights or for company presidents.”
Mr. Firer was in charge of the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaire’s Fair, a four-day consumer orgy held at an event center near the capital.
In addition to Gulfstream, 200 other luxury suppliers had installed their exhibition stands, hoping to attract the new wealthy Russians to all kinds of products, from mahogany-crafted yachts to diamond-embedded car grills, worth 50 cents.
Mr. Firer looks carefully at a bright orange Porsche in the stand next to his."
“It’s a nice car, but it’s nickel and cauldron compared to us,” he said.
“After the United States, Russia is the second largest market for private jets.”
Fueled by the boom in oil, the Russian capital looks like Dallas when it was at its peak.
“We lived the same way in 1890, when some wealthy Americans came to meet in Europe, where they were seen as materialists,” says Marshall Goldman, a senior professor at the Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies at Harvard University.
“Like the Saudis of the 1970s and the Japanese of the 1990s, the Russians are emerging as the world’s biggest consumers and spenders.”
The world’s most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share of the cake.
Elsewhere in Moscow, a conference on the luxury industry will be held this week with Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, the president of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell luxury goods in markets such as Russia.
