The Federal Reserve is expected to cut rates to raise the stock market
Shares jumped on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday after the market expected the Federal Reserve to ease credit conditions with interest rate cuts, which increased with reassuring comments from the vice president of the U.S. central bank.
Stock markets were slumped in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, number two to Ben Bernanke, chairman of the reserve, declared that policymakers should be “flexible and pragmatic” in responding to the continued strain of financial markets.
In a clear effort to reassure markets amid growing samples of credit exchanges, Mr Kohn said the recent turbulence was "partly reversed by market improvement in late September and during October."
If the upward trend persists, it would increase the possibility of further adjustments in financial conditions for real estate and business, Kohn said.
The comments were taken by investors as a sign that the reserve is ready to inject fresh capital into U.S. markets and to make further interest rate cuts, to stabilize credit conditions.
Observations also helped calm Wall Street amid bad news for the U.S. economy, such as home sales that hit the lowest record in October.
The consequences of the financial turmoil were accentuated by a warning from Bear Stearns, an investment bank that will cut 650 jobs, equivalent to 4% of its total workforce, in a global cost reduction to offset losses from its investments in U.S. sub-prime mortgages.
Only 20 of those jobs are expected to enter London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
