Pressure on the Bank of England to follow the action of the Federal Reserve and the ECB and inject extra funds into the stock markets in London, strained credit and rates of three-month “Libor” loans among British banks, the biggest rise since September, of 6.59%, after a steady rise since November 12.
England sues Owais Shah and Ravi Bopara
Here are two dilemmas, each as difficult as the other.
Who should hit No. 6 for England in Kandy this weekend, Owais Shah or Ravi Bopara?
And, none are less important than the first test against Sri Lanka, who should make the decision?
The second question is relevant because David Graveney, the chairman of the team who is on loan--with that particular title at least, is here to help Peter Moores, the coach, and Michael Vaughan, the captain, decide; and also because the desk of Hugh Morris, director of England, is starting to fill with offers to become a national selector part, and if not, in one.
He who does not get the sixth place in batting will be unfortunate, but life is often unfair and the sport too.
It is not easy to throw what one man does at the top of his profession, while another never goes beyond the lower level, sometimes for lack of luck rather than ability.
Not only in cricket the choice is difficult, as it requires judgements that always end up being subjective.
Is it the right time for Bopara to stand up?
Is it fair to Shah if he does?
The same question could be asked in another way if, says John Edwards or “Tubby” Banerjee, two brilliant young executives with good grades and who know the business well, were to be promoted to the board: there is only room for one of them.
