Venus: twin brother of Earth.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that until now had not been raised. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls at the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that there might be rays on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays are silent from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California at Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of the origin of Urey-Miller's life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms may have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it’s not like that: if there were life there someday, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C reign on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Possibly Venus is a 'diabolical' twin of Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main goal of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of "Nature", according to the researchers, emphasize not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had expected,” ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers also discovered in the southern polar region a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high Earth atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has almost the same mass as Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called the dawn star or evening star orbits the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: a day on Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar does not closely resemble Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
Water had clumped on both planets and remained in the oceans on Earth, but on Venus it dissociated in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
