It's not the wooden boxes.
Whoever relates the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but does not think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol’s list of works.
Most of the ninety-four "type" Shine-Boxes on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" put the doubt about the authenticity of the 1968 Brillo-Boxes artifacts found in Andy Warhol, the Museum Moderna Museet in Stockholm carried out internal investigations and came to disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director of the museum Pontus Hulténa reg<0xC3><0xB3>los, and the former director of the Museum Moderna regula.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted the wooden boxes in red, blue and white, with the same sample that had "Brillo" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, in the exhibition of his 1968 works at the Moderna Museet there were exposed hundreds of Gloss-cardboard boxes. These were not made by Warhol (because of the expenses), but were brought directly from the "Brillo" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but specimens (which were only objects) exhibited.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed the production of wood-boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Modern Museum.
Witnesses of that time now speak of nearly fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auction as originals of the "Stockholm-type" "Bright-Boxes" authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auctions, some of them were bought for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous museum director Pontus Hultén made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost one hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malm<0xC3><0xB6> for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Bystr<0xC3><0xB6>m, the head of curators at the Moderna Museet museum, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. They were first printed and ground their tight silvers and then painted them in oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the copies of the year 1990 shows that the painting was applied with a roller without directly printing the pressed silvers. In addition, it is not about oil painting, but acrylic painting.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from Andy Warhol's official glossy-box list," says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet Museum and adds that if the "Andy Warhol Art" Authentication Commission in New York fails to come to any conclusion, the Moderna Museet Museum will classify these six boxes as ex-copies.
Already in July, the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these “serious accusations” that they are soap powder boxes.
But from that moment on, everything remained in absolute silence.
